---
// src/layouts/Base.astro — M-UX T1 deliverable.
//
// Per ADR-0002 (https://.../adr/0002_ux_layer_mdn_three_column.md):
// MDN-docs three-column chrome on desktop (≥1024px), single column
// with mobile-drawer affordance below 1024px. T1 lands the *shell*;
// T2–T7 fill the named slots:
//
//   slot="breadcrumb"  — T3 mounts `Breadcrumb.astro` here. T7
//                        adds the hamburger drawer-trigger inside
//                        `Breadcrumb.astro`'s component-internal
//                        slot (NOT a Base-level slot — resolves
//                        MUX-BO-ISS-04 / MEDIUM-1).
//   slot="left-rail"   — T2 mounts the chapter-list nav.
//   slot=(default)     — chapter content (existing routes flow
//                        their `<header>` + `<article>` into this
//                        slot unchanged).
//   slot="right-rail"  — T4 mounts TOC + scroll-spy + (in
//                        interactive mode, T6) the annotations
//                        pane.
//   slot="drawer"      — T7 mounts the mobile-drawer overlay
//                        (`Drawer.astro`'s aside + backdrop). Lives
//                        OUTSIDE `.chrome` so the fixed-position
//                        drawer escapes the sticky-breadcrumb
//                        stacking context (z-index: 50). Empty when
//                        no consumer fills it — index page does not
//                        mount a drawer (no left rail to drawer-ify).
//
// Slots are declared with no fallback content — chapters that
// don't fill them render an empty named region without breaking
// layout (the grid track is reserved either way; emptiness is
// expected during the M-UX rollout while T2–T7 are still
// outstanding).
//
// M3 contracts preserved verbatim from the prior 51-line shell:
//
//   1. Inline script imports `detectMode()` and sets
//      `<body data-mode="static|interactive">`. This is the T5
//      bootstrap that gates every `data-interactive-only` element.
//   2. Global CSS rule
//        `body[data-mode="static"] [data-interactive-only] { display: none !important; }`
//      hides interactive-only surfaces on the public deploy. T6/T7
//      components (annotations, mark-read) carry the attribute and
//      stay invisible in static mode.
//   3. The "interactive mode active" floating badge stays — it's
//      only rendered when `data-mode="interactive"` (via the same
//      `data-interactive-only` rule).
//
// M-UX-REVIEW T6 update (2026-04-27): typography pair pinned per
// ADR-0002 amendment + UI-review F11. The body font-family on
// `:global(body)` switched from `var(--mux-font-sans)` (the M-UX-era
// system stack) to `var(--mux-font-body)` (Source Sans 3 + system
// fallback chain — see `src/styles/chrome.css` token + `@font-face`
// declarations). Mono token name is unchanged but its primary family
// is now JetBrains Mono. `font-display: swap` keeps page boot
// non-blocking; the brief FOUT renders in the system fallback. No
// layout / template changes here — typography swap is a token-level
// edit.
//
// Article-wrapper contract (resolves MUX-BO-ISS-01 / HIGH-1):
//   This layout does NOT wrap the default slot in `<article>`. The
//   chapter routes (`src/pages/{lectures,notes,practice}/[id].astro`)
//   own the `<article>` wrapper. M3's `MarkReadButton.astro`
//   (line 70) queries `article a[id^="ch_"]` for its
//   IntersectionObserver — replacing `<article>` with `<div class>`
//   here would silently break "current section" detection. Every
//   route's existing `<article>` survives the T1 rewrite untouched;
//   T1's `<main slot>` simply receives them.
//
// Layout grid + Base-only CSS lives inline below. Shared design
// tokens (accent, font-stack, column widths, breakpoint reference)
// live in `src/styles/chrome.css` — imported globally so chrome
// components in T2/T3/T4/T7 reach the same vars. Boundary doc at
// the top of `chrome.css`.
//
// M-UX T9 update (2026-04-25): two CSS-only refinements per spec
// D1 + D2.
//   D1 — centered chrome on wide viewports. `.chrome` gets
//        `max-width: var(--mux-chrome-max); margin-inline: auto` so
//        at >1400px the three-column grid stays centered instead of
//        stretching across the whole viewport (rails were floating
//        100s of pixels away from content edges on 2560px+ displays).
//        At ≤1400px the existing 260px / 1fr / 280px grid is unchanged
//        — rails snug to viewport edges as before.
//   D2 — sticky rails with internal scroll at ≥1024px. The left and
//        right rails (aside[data-slot="left-rail"], aside[data-slot=
//        "right-rail"]) follow the user down long chapters via
//        `position: sticky`. `align-self: start` is non-negotiable —
//        without it the sticky aside fills its grid cell and has zero
//        stick range. Top offset is `var(--mux-breadcrumb-height)`
//        so the rails sit directly under the sticky breadcrumb. The
//        rails are also given `max-height: calc(100vh - breadcrumb -
//        gutter)` + `overflow-y: auto` so a 12-item chapter list +
//        TOC + annotations pane scrolls inside the rail rather than
//        overflowing the viewport on 768px-tall displays.
// Mobile (<1024px) drawer behaviour is unchanged — sticky rules sit
// inside the existing ≥1024px @media block.
//
// M-UX-REVIEW T4 update (2026-04-27): D1 + D2 reshape mobile chrome.
//   D1 (UI-review F9, HIGH) hides the breadcrumb at <768px. The hide
//   is a single CSS rule on the outer breadcrumb slot wrapper which
//   now carries the `.breadcrumb-bar` class. The drawer trigger
//   used to mount inside the breadcrumb's flex row (M-UX T7); it
//   now mounts at chrome-level via the new `drawer-trigger` named
//   slot so the trigger survives the breadcrumb hide. The slot is
//   a row ABOVE the breadcrumb in the grid template; at ≥1024px the
//   trigger has `display: none` (DrawerTrigger.astro media query)
//   so the auto-sized row collapses with no content. At 768-1023px
//   (tablet) the trigger sits as its own row above the visible
//   breadcrumb (a minor visual change for tablet sizes vs the
//   pre-T4 in-breadcrumb placement; acceptable per spec since the
//   trigger is unchanged in function).
//
//   D2 (UI-review F9 continued) repositions the "On this page"
//   `<details>` block to render below the chapter H1 + collection
//   tabs at <768px. The desktop right-rail TOC stays in the
//   right-rail aside. The mobile details is rendered by a separate
//   component (`MobileChapterTOC.astro`) inside the chapter route's
//   `<header>` after `<CollectionTabs>`. At <768px the right-rail
//   aside hides (`display: none`) so the mobile details is the only
//   TOC surface; at ≥768px the mobile details hides and the desktop
//   right rail takes over. Two SSR renders, no shared selectors —
//   the mobile component uses a distinct `.rhs-toc-mobile` class
//   that ScrollSpy + RightRailReadStatus do NOT query, so the
//   desktop islands keep operating against a single canonical
//   `.right-rail-toc` instance regardless of viewport.
//
// M-UX-REVIEW T1 update (2026-04-27): D3 adds a tiny always-loaded
// `<script>` that records the current chapter route to localStorage
// under the key `cs300:last-visit` so the home + collection-landing
// pages can render a "Continue reading" resume card via
// `src/components/home/ContinueReading.astro`. The writer fires on
// every chapter route (Base.astro is only used by chapter routes;
// the four landing surfaces use HomeLayout.astro), so the spec D3
// "skip writes on the four landing pages" requirement is satisfied
// structurally — the writer literally cannot run on a landing page
// because Base.astro never renders them. Strictly browser-local —
// no state-service round-trip, no SQLite touch. Replaced by M5's
// SQLite-backed dashboard slot when the review queue lands.
//
// Companion files:
//   - design_docs/architecture.md §1.6 (Page chrome — UX layer)
//   - design_docs/adr/0002_ux_layer_mdn_three_column.md
//   - design_docs/milestones/m_ux_polish/tasks/T1_layout_shell.md
//   - design_docs/milestones/m_ux_polish/tasks/T9_layout_polish.md (D1+D2)
//   - design_docs/milestones/m_ux_review/tasks/T1_home_surface.md (D3)
//   - src/components/home/ContinueReading.astro (reader side of the
//     localStorage primitive)
import '../styles/chrome.css';
// M-UX-REVIEW followup (2026-04-27) — KaTeX CSS import. Without this,
// `rehype-katex` emits both `<span class="katex-mathml">` (intended for
// AT) and `<span class="katex-html">` (visual) but the position/clip
// rule that visually hides the MathML never applies, so every $…$
// expression renders twice (e.g. "key → → bucket"). Pre-existing bug
// since M2 — the issue surfaced in the 2026-04-27 deploy review.
import 'katex/dist/katex.min.css';
import BackToTop from '../components/chrome/BackToTop.astro';

interface Props {
  title?: string;
}

const { title = 'cs-300' } = Astro.props;
---

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width" />
    <meta name="generator" content={Astro.generator} />
    <link rel="icon" type="image/svg+xml" href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}favicon.svg`} />
    <title>{title}</title>
    <style is:global>
      /* T5 contract: hide interactive-only surfaces in static mode.
         Preserved unchanged from the pre-M-UX shell. */
      body[data-mode="static"] [data-interactive-only] {
        display: none !important;
      }
    </style>
    <style>
      /* ============================================================
         Layout grid — T1 deliverable.
         Base-only rules; component-internal rules live with the
         components in `src/components/chrome/*` and the shared tokens
         live in `src/styles/chrome.css`.
         ============================================================ */

      /* Page-level reset minimum — keep narrow; the visual sweep
         (deferred per ADR-0002) owns broader typography work. */
      :global(html),
      :global(body) {
        margin: 0;
        padding: 0;
      }
      :global(body) {
        font-family: var(--mux-font-body);
        color: var(--mux-fg);
        background: var(--mux-surface);
        line-height: 1.6;
      }

      /* Three-column desktop grid (≥1024px). Named template areas
         keep slot wiring legible even when one or more rails are
         empty during the T2/T3/T4 rollout.

         Mobile (<1024px) re-order (T7): the right-rail slot moves
         ABOVE main so the in-chapter TOC (T4) + AnnotationsPane
         (T6), each wrapped in a `<details>` collapsed-by-default,
         appear at content top per ADR-0002 + architecture.md §1.6.
         At <1024px the left-rail slot is removed from the grid
         flow (`grid-area` is no longer named in the template
         below) and the `<aside>` itself becomes a fixed
         off-canvas drawer — see the dedicated @media block lower
         in this file (T7 cycle 2 refactor; resolves
         M-UX-T7-ISS-02 + ISS-03 by collapsing the cycle 1
         twice-render into a single DOM tree). */
      .chrome {
        display: grid;
        min-height: 100vh;
        grid-template-columns: 1fr;
        /* Mobile template (<1024px): no left-rail track. The aside
           still exists in the document, but it's pulled out of the
           grid flow and styled `position: fixed` by the @media
           block below so it can slide in/out as the drawer.
           T4 D1 adds a leading `drawer-trigger` row above the
           breadcrumb so the hamburger button survives the
           breadcrumb-hide at <768px. At ≥1024px the trigger has
           display:none (via DrawerTrigger.astro's own media query)
           so the auto-sized row collapses with no content. */
        grid-template-areas:
          "drawer-trigger"
          "breadcrumb"
          "right-rail"
          "main";
        /* T9 D1 — centered chrome on wide viewports. At ≤1400px the
           grid fills the viewport (max-width is inert when the
           viewport is narrower than `--mux-chrome-max`). At >1400px
           `margin-inline: auto` centers the grid + leaves equal
           gutters to the viewport edges so the three columns don't
           drift apart. Width: 100% keeps the inline-size at the
           parent's full track when below the cap.

           Note: this does NOT break the sticky breadcrumb. The
           breadcrumb's containing block is `.chrome` (because it's
           a direct grid child); `position: sticky; top: 0` measures
           from the viewport top, so the breadcrumb still pins to
           the top of the viewport when the user scrolls. The
           `min-height: 100vh` + tall page content keep its stick
           range intact (T8 cycle 1's M-UX-T3-ISS-01 fix preserved). */
        max-width: var(--mux-chrome-max);
        margin-inline: auto;
        width: 100%;
      }

      .chrome > [data-slot="drawer-trigger"] { grid-area: drawer-trigger; }
      .chrome > [data-slot="breadcrumb"] { grid-area: breadcrumb; }
      .chrome > [data-slot="main"]       { grid-area: main; min-width: 0; }
      .chrome > [data-slot="right-rail"] { grid-area: right-rail; }

      /* T4 D1 — drawer-trigger row padding. Mirrors the breadcrumb's
         own padding so a tablet that shows both rows (<1024px and
         ≥768px) reads as a tidy stack, not a misaligned column.
         At ≥1024px the trigger inside collapses to display:none and
         the row's intrinsic height becomes zero — the padding is
         inert there because the row collapses too. */
      .chrome > [data-slot="drawer-trigger"] {
        padding: var(--mux-space-2) var(--mux-space-4);
      }
      /* When the slot is empty (e.g. an index page that doesn't
         mount a DrawerTrigger), zero out the padding so the row
         doesn't reserve visual space. The :empty pseudo-class
         matches because the slot wrapper has no element children
         when no consumer fills it. */
      .chrome > [data-slot="drawer-trigger"]:empty {
        display: none;
      }

      /* Center column constrains prose width for readability per
         ADR-0002 ("max-width ~75ch"). The constraint applies inside
         the `<main>` slot, leaving the rails free to use full track
         width. */
      .chrome > [data-slot="main"] {
        padding: var(--mux-space-6) var(--mux-space-4);
      }
      .chrome > [data-slot="main"] > :global(*) {
        max-width: var(--mux-content-max);
      }
      /* Article wrapper (chapter content) gets the same constraint
         + a margin reset so prose centers within the column. */
      .chrome > [data-slot="main"] :global(article) {
        max-width: var(--mux-content-max);
      }

      /* Rails get their own padding so the slot content (T2/T4) can
         focus on its own structure without re-doing inset spacing. */
      .chrome > [data-slot="left-rail"],
      .chrome > [data-slot="right-rail"] {
        padding: var(--mux-space-4);
      }

      /* Breadcrumb slot reserves a row even when empty; T3 mounts
         the Breadcrumb component which owns its own internal styles.
         T8 cycle 1 (M-UX-T3-ISS-01 / MEDIUM): sticky positioning lives
         on this OUTER slot wrapper, not on the inner `<nav
         class="breadcrumb">` Breadcrumb.astro emits. The slot wrapper
         is a direct grid child of `.chrome` (which has `min-height:
         100vh` plus tall content), so its containing block has real
         stick range. The inner nav previously carried `position:
         sticky` but its containing block was THIS outer wrapper —
         which was auto-sized to the inner nav's own height, leaving
         zero stick range. T8's harness scroll-test (.smoke/screenshots
         /lectures-ch4-1280x800-midscroll-T3.png) confirmed the
         breadcrumb scrolled out of view alongside the chapter
         content; moving sticky here is the option (a) fix the T3
         issue file recommended. */
      .chrome > [data-slot="breadcrumb"] {
        position: sticky;
        top: 0;
        z-index: 50;
        border-bottom: 1px solid var(--mux-border-subtle);
        background: var(--mux-surface);
      }

      /* ≥1024px — three-column grid (per ADR-0002). Column widths
         260/1fr/280 are pinned in `chrome.css` (--mux-col-left-rail,
         --mux-col-right-rail) and re-stated here because @media
         queries can't read custom properties as track values.
         At desktop the left-rail aside reclaims its `grid-area`
         placement (the mobile template above intentionally omits
         it so the aside doesn't reserve track space when it's
         repositioned as the off-canvas drawer at <1024px). */
      @media (min-width: 1024px) {
        .chrome {
          grid-template-columns: 260px 1fr 280px;
          /* Desktop template — the leading `drawer-trigger` row
             from the mobile template is dropped because the
             trigger is hidden at ≥1024px (DrawerTrigger.astro's own
             media query). The slot wrapper itself stays in the DOM
             (chapter routes always pass <DrawerTrigger>), so the
             `:empty` rule above doesn't fire (the wrapper has a
             child even when that child is `display:none`); we hide
             the wrapper explicitly here to keep it out of the
             implicit grid track Chrome would otherwise place it in
             at the bottom of `.chrome`. */
          grid-template-areas:
            "breadcrumb breadcrumb breadcrumb"
            "left-rail  main       right-rail";
        }
        .chrome > [data-slot="drawer-trigger"] {
          display: none;
        }
        .chrome > [data-slot="left-rail"] {
          grid-area: left-rail;
          border-right: 1px solid var(--mux-border-subtle);
        }
        .chrome > [data-slot="right-rail"] {
          border-left: 1px solid var(--mux-border-subtle);
        }
        .chrome > [data-slot="main"] {
          padding: var(--mux-space-6) var(--mux-space-8);
        }

        /* T9 D2 — sticky rails on desktop. Both asides become
           position: sticky so they follow the user down long
           chapters (ch_4 lectures has ~80 sections; without sticky
           rails the user scrolls past the chapter nav 200 lines in
           and has no quick path back to other chapters or to the
           in-chapter TOC).

           - `position: sticky; top: var(--mux-breadcrumb-height)`
             pins the rail directly under the sticky breadcrumb.
           - `align-self: start` is CRITICAL. Without it the sticky
             aside fills its grid cell (default `align-self: stretch`
             on grid items) so its bottom edge is at the bottom of
             the cell — there's nothing to "stick" because the
             element height equals the scroll container height,
             leaving zero stick range. With `align-self: start` the
             aside shrink-wraps to its content height and gets real
             stick range.
           - `max-height: calc(100vh - breadcrumb - gutter)` + scroll
             so a 12-item chapter list + TOC + annotations pane that
             together exceed the viewport height (768px-tall windows
             are common) scroll inside the rail rather than off-
             screen. The gutter (var(--mux-space-2)) is a small
             safety margin so the bottom edge doesn't kiss the
             viewport edge.

           The @media wrapper means these rules don't apply at
           <1024px, where the left-rail aside is repositioned as a
           fixed off-canvas drawer (see the existing max-width:
           1023.98px block below) and the right-rail aside is in
           normal flow above main. Sticky behaviour on a fixed-
           position drawer would be meaningless. */
        .chrome > [data-slot="left-rail"],
        .chrome > [data-slot="right-rail"] {
          position: sticky;
          top: var(--mux-breadcrumb-height);
          align-self: start;
          max-height: calc(100vh - var(--mux-breadcrumb-height) - var(--mux-space-2));
          overflow-y: auto;
        }
      }

      /* T7 cycle 2 — Mobile drawer (single DOM tree).
         At <1024px, the SAME `<aside data-slot="left-rail">` that
         renders as the desktop left rail becomes a fixed off-canvas
         drawer. CSS handles the slide; `Drawer.astro`'s JS island
         toggles `body.drawer-open` when the hamburger
         (`DrawerTrigger.astro`) fires `cs300:drawer-toggle`. No
         second LeftRail mount: the duplicate-id finding
         (M-UX-T7-ISS-03) and the +700 KB twice-rendered JSON
         payload (M-UX-T7-ISS-02) both vanish.

         z-index 9999 keeps the drawer above the backdrop (9998 in
         Drawer.astro) and above the body-level interactive
         affordances (z=1000), which `body.drawer-open` rules
         further suppress to belt-and-braces level.

         Width capped at min(280px, 85vw) so narrow phones don't
         get a drawer that covers the whole screen and so 280px
         matches `--mux-col-left-rail` on desktop (visual register
         is identical when the user resizes across the breakpoint).

         The aside is rendered in the document but its
         `transform: translateX(-100%)` keeps it off-screen until
         `body.drawer-open` flips the transform to translateX(0).
         Index page has no left-rail content (its slot is empty) so
         the rules are inert there.

         Empty-rail discipline: when the `<aside>` is empty (e.g.
         the index page never mounts a LeftRail), the rule still
         applies but the off-canvas aside is invisible + has no
         focusables, so it's truly inert.
         */
      @media (max-width: 1023.98px) {
        .chrome > [data-slot="left-rail"] {
          position: fixed;
          top: 0;
          left: 0;
          height: 100vh;
          width: min(280px, 85vw);
          max-width: 320px;
          padding: var(--mux-space-3) var(--mux-space-4);
          background: var(--mux-surface);
          border-right: 1px solid var(--mux-border-subtle);
          box-shadow: 2px 0 12px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
          transform: translateX(-100%);
          transition: transform 200ms ease;
          z-index: 9999;
          overflow-y: auto;
        }
        :global(body.drawer-open) .chrome > [data-slot="left-rail"] {
          transform: translateX(0);
        }
      }

      /* Floating "interactive mode active" badge — preserved from
         the prior shell. `data-interactive-only` keeps it absent in
         static mode. */
      .interactive-badge {
        position: fixed;
        bottom: 8px;
        right: 8px;
        font-size: .75rem;
        background: var(--mux-accent);
        color: #fff;
        padding: 2px 8px;
        border-radius: 4px;
        z-index: 1000;
      }

      /* T7 — Mobile responsive sweep.
         Center column padding tightens at narrow widths so prose
         doesn't hit the viewport edge but also doesn't waste a
         third of the screen on inset. Typography stays at the base
         size; ADR-0002 explicitly defers full-typography sweep to a
         post-M-UX follow-on.

         M-UX-REVIEW T4 (2026-04-27) layered three rules onto this
         block:
           D1 — `.breadcrumb-bar { display: none }` hides the
                breadcrumb track at <768px (UI-review F9). The
                drawer-trigger slot above it stays visible because
                its row collapses with `:empty` only when the slot
                has no content; chapter routes pass <DrawerTrigger>
                into the slot, so the row keeps its intrinsic
                height + padding.
           D2 — at <768px hide the desktop right-rail TOC track
                (`aside[data-slot="right-rail"] .right-rail-toc`)
                AND the M-UX T7 mobile-collapse `<details>`
                wrapper (`aside[data-slot="right-rail"]
                details.toc-mobile-collapse`); the chapter route's
                `<header>`-mounted `<MobileChapterTOC>` (rendered
                as a sibling of `<CollectionTabs>`) takes over as
                the on-this-page affordance below the H1 + tabs.
                The mobile component itself is hidden at ≥768px
                via its own component rule so the desktop
                right-rail TOC remains the single TOC surface
                above the breakpoint.
                Cycle 2 narrowed the hide from the whole aside
                to the inner TOC selectors so AnnotationsPane —
                a sibling of RightRailTOC inside the same aside —
                survives the mobile media query in interactive
                mode (M-UX T7 line 19 + ADR-0002 line 75
                contracts; see issue file MEDIUM-1 option (a)). */
      @media (max-width: 767.98px) {
        .chrome > [data-slot="main"] {
          padding: var(--mux-space-4) var(--mux-space-3);
        }
        /* T4 D1 — hide the breadcrumb track entirely. The drawer
           trigger sits in its own row above the breadcrumb (see
           grid-template-areas), so navigation affordances survive
           the hide. Prev/next chapter buttons collapse into the
           drawer's chapter list at this width per spec. */
        .chrome > [data-slot="breadcrumb"].breadcrumb-bar {
          display: none;
        }
        /* T4 D2 — hide the right-rail TOC track at mobile. The
           in-chapter TOC affordance moves to the route's
           `<MobileChapterTOC>` rendered after `<CollectionTabs>`
           inside `<header>`. We hide instead of `grid-template-
           areas`-removing because the aside still hosts the
           desktop SSR TOC + RightRailReadStatus + ScrollSpy
           islands — they need to stay in the DOM so a viewport
           resize back to ≥768px finds them already mounted.

           T4 cycle 2 (M-UX-REVIEW-T4-ISS-01 option a — narrow
           hide): the prior rule
           `.chrome > aside[data-slot="right-rail"] { display: none }`
           hid the entire aside, which propagated `display: none`
           to AnnotationsPane (mounted as a child of the same
           aside per `lectures/[id].astro:167`) and silently
           broke the M-UX T7 line 19 + ADR-0002 line 75
           AnnotationsPane-in-right-rail-at-mobile contract in
           interactive mode. The narrowed rules below hide ONLY
           the desktop TOC track (`.right-rail-toc` — the
           `<nav>` RightRailTOC.astro emits) and the M-UX T7
           mobile-collapse `<details>` wrapper around it
           (`details.toc-mobile-collapse`). The aside itself
           stays in flow; AnnotationsPane (gated
           `data-interactive-only`) renders only when interactive
           mode flips. The on-this-page affordance for static +
           interactive mobile lives in `<MobileChapterTOC>`
           inside `<header>` per T4 D2 — see CHANGELOG entry
           "M-UX-REVIEW T4 cycle-2 closure" + the issue file. */
        aside[data-slot="right-rail"] :global(.right-rail-toc) {
          display: none;
        }
        aside[data-slot="right-rail"] :global(details.toc-mobile-collapse) {
          display: none;
        }
      }

      /* T7 — When the drawer is open at <1024px, lock body scroll
         and suppress the body-level fixed-position interactive
         affordances so they don't paint on top of the drawer overlay
         (drawer aside z-index sits inside its own root stacking
         context via the `slot="drawer"` placement; the body-level
         z=1000 elements live outside that context and would
         otherwise occlude the drawer at the bottom of the viewport).
         The static-mode public deploy never reaches this state —
         AnnotateButton + MarkReadButton + interactive-badge all
         carry `data-interactive-only`, hidden in static mode. */
      :global(body.drawer-open) {
        overflow: hidden;
      }
      :global(body.drawer-open #annotate-button),
      :global(body.drawer-open #mark-read-button),
      :global(body.drawer-open .interactive-badge) {
        display: none !important;
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body data-mode="static">
    <div class="chrome">
      <div data-slot="drawer-trigger">
        {/* M-UX-REVIEW T4 D1 — drawer-trigger lives at chrome level
            (not inside the breadcrumb bar) so it survives the
            breadcrumb-hide at <768px. Routes that don't need a
            drawer (index, landing pages) leave this slot empty;
            the `:empty { display: none }` rule above keeps the
            row from reserving visual space. */}
        <slot name="drawer-trigger" />
      </div>
      <nav class="breadcrumb-bar" data-slot="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        {/* M-UX-REVIEW T4 D1 — `.breadcrumb-bar` is the styling hook
            the <768px hide rule binds to (`@media (max-width: 767px)
            .breadcrumb-bar { display: none }`). The class is on the
            outer slot wrapper so the entire breadcrumb track —
            including the inner `<nav class="breadcrumb">` and any
            future siblings — vanishes from layout in one rule. */}
        <slot name="breadcrumb" />
      </nav>
      <aside id="drawer" data-slot="left-rail" aria-label="Chapter navigation">
        {/* `id="drawer"` is the focus-trap + aria-controls target for
            DrawerTrigger.astro at <1024px. T7 cycle 2: this is the
            ONE LeftRail mount; CSS in this file slides it in/out as
            the drawer at <1024px. At desktop the id is harmless. */}
        <slot name="left-rail" />
      </aside>
      <main data-slot="main">
        <slot />
      </main>
      <aside data-slot="right-rail" aria-label="Section navigation and annotations">
        <slot name="right-rail" />
      </aside>
    </div>
    {/* Drawer overlay slot (M-UX T7). Rendered OUTSIDE `.chrome` so
        the drawer's `position: fixed` element does not inherit the
        sticky-breadcrumb stacking context (`position: sticky;
        z-index: 50` would otherwise trap z-index inside the
        breadcrumb's local layer, leaving body-level `z-index: 1000`
        siblings — AnnotateButton, MarkReadButton, the interactive
        badge — painting on top of the open drawer). T7's
        `Drawer.astro` mounts here. Empty slot has zero markup
        impact when no consumer fills it. */}
    <slot name="drawer" />
    <BackToTop />
    <div data-interactive-only class="interactive-badge">interactive mode active</div>
    <script>
      import { detectMode } from '../lib/mode';
      detectMode().then((mode) => {
        document.body.dataset.mode = mode;
      });
    </script>
    <script is:inline>
      // M-UX-REVIEW T1 D3 — continue-reading writer.
      // Records the current chapter route to localStorage under
      // `cs300:last-visit` so the home + collection-landing pages
      // can render a resume card. Inline because the body is small
      // and we want the write to land before any user-initiated
      // navigation (e.g. user clicks a sibling chapter link before
      // module bundle is parsed). Strictly browser-local; no
      // state-service round-trip. See companion reader at
      // `src/components/home/ContinueReading.astro`.
      (function () {
        try {
          var path = window.location.pathname;
          // Defensive guard: only persist when the path looks like a
          // chapter route (Base.astro renders only chapter routes
          // today, but the regex makes the contract explicit so a
          // future Base.astro consumer can't silently corrupt the
          // resume entry with a non-chapter route).
          if (!/\/(lectures|notes|practice)\/ch_\d+\/?$/.test(path)) return;
          var write = function () {
            try {
              window.localStorage.setItem(
                'cs300:last-visit',
                JSON.stringify({
                  path: path,
                  title: document.title,
                  scrollY: Math.round(window.scrollY || 0),
                  ts: Date.now(),
                })
              );
            } catch (_err) {
              // Quota / private-mode / disabled storage — silent
              // degradation; the resume card simply never paints.
            }
          };
          // Initial write on load so the entry exists even if the
          // user never scrolls.
          write();
          // Debounced scroll listener — at most ~4 writes/sec
          // (250ms throttle). The whole point is the most-recent
          // scrollY; precise sub-second granularity isn't worth the
          // localStorage churn.
          var pending = false;
          window.addEventListener(
            'scroll',
            function () {
              if (pending) return;
              pending = true;
              setTimeout(function () {
                pending = false;
                write();
              }, 250);
            },
            { passive: true }
          );
        } catch (_err) {
          // Catch-all so a hostile environment can't break page boot.
        }
      })();
    </script>
  </body>
</html>
